Continuing county level mega found this morning by A. Merritt. 5th county record per eBird, I believe.  Huge shout-out to Alex for the find, LC for the heads up, and Everett and Bob for the solid recon. Teamwork makes the dream work.  We missed it on our first pass and walked to the tree near the lighthouse steps where Everett had it earlier, without luck. When we returned to the area around the bathrooms, we immediately saw it on the hillside slightly to the north. It then flew close to the path right across from the residence, and better photos were obtained. We then watched it fly into the cypress trees and on the hillside around the residence and path. It would disappear easily, and then reappear in an instant. Awesome looks.   ID'ed as CAKI due to lack of white on outer rectrices, white chin and malar, yellow on breast not extending to upper breast, short tail, and overall grayness of the bird. Fairly worn. WEKI and other yellow-bellied kingbird sp. ruled out by the above field marks. Mark got some great flight shots. Preliminarily aged and sexed as adult female due to slightly emarginated outer primaries, not nearly as much as would be expected for an adult male, and juvs lack this feature on primary tips. Open to feedback about age/sex. The bird vocalized very briefly twice, but nothing diagnostic. Sweet bird!

Locality: Chestnut Hill Lane - Cassin's Kingbird location
Observation Details: First seen as I was driving down the road, just north of the intersection. It flew right in front of me, and I knew it was different right away. When it banked and flew off to the side of the road I saw the yellowish belly and dark tail and initially thought this was a Western Kingbird. I pulled over and got out of my car. In a short time I was looking at the bird a little ways (100 feet) off the road. I throught I needed photos so I got my camera out and started shooting. I put out the alert to my local Telegram group and put a few of the photos on here and after a short discussiion with several others, we realized this was a Cassin's Kingbird instead. Within 45 minutes I had six other local birders here and we all had great scope views. The bird was very skittish and would not allow people to get close to it, and when a car would come down the road it flushed away from the roadside and landed out in the field aways. After a short time it would return to the roadside area and hunt over the grasses in the ditch. It would then land in the plowed field, anywhere from a foot to ten feet away from the edge of the grass. When I first saw it, and before other arrived, it did land a few times in the middle of the gravel road.   This bird had a medium colored yellow belly, a dark gray hooded head and a clearly seen whitish chin area. The tail was dark, but not a solid black like I've seen on Western Kingbirds. I'll post photos and at least two videos I took of it.

Locality: Chestnut Hill Lane - Cassin's Kingbird location
Observation Details: First seen as I was driving down the road, just north of the intersection. It flew right in front of me, and I knew it was different right away. When it banked and flew off to the side of the road I saw the yellowish belly and dark tail and initially thought this was a Western Kingbird. I pulled over and got out of my car. In a short time I was looking at the bird a little ways (100 feet) off the road. I throught I needed photos so I got my camera out and started shooting. I put out the alert to my local Telegram group and put a few of the photos on here and after a short discussiion with several others, we realized this was a Cassin's Kingbird instead. Within 45 minutes I had six other local birders here and we all had great scope views. The bird was very skittish and would not allow people to get close to it, and when a car would come down the road it flushed away from the roadside and landed out in the field aways. After a short time it would return to the roadside area and hunt over the grasses in the ditch. It would then land in the plowed field, anywhere from a foot to ten feet away from the edge of the grass. When I first saw it, and before other arrived, it did land a few times in the middle of the gravel road.   This bird had a medium colored yellow belly, a dark gray hooded head and a clearly seen whitish chin area. The tail was dark, but not a solid black like I've seen on Western Kingbirds. I'll post photos and at least two videos I took of it.

Media notes: Adult feeding fledgling
Observation Details: Two adults feeding four fledglings in a large magnolia (or similar) tree. Observed over the course of 20 minutes, the juveniles were sometimes huddled together in pairs, or resting individually, sometimes with eyes closed. But mostly they were alert and would gather immediately with short flights when an adult arrived with food. Food deliveries took place every few minutes and included red berries and insects (photos suggest bees). Each food delivery was given to one individual. Adults did not stay with the young for more than a few seconds, although sometimes they perched at the top of the tree for a few minutes at a time. The young called constantly with typical "ch-beer" calls which were slightly thinner and buzzier than the adult calls.

Observation Details: Continuing county level mega found this morning by A. Merritt. 5th county record per eBird, I believe.  Huge shout-out to Alex for the find, LC for the heads up, and Everett and Bob for the solid recon. Teamwork makes the dream work.  We missed it on our first pass and walked to the tree near the lighthouse steps where Everett had it earlier, without luck. When we returned to the area around the bathrooms, we immediately saw it on the hillside slightly to the north. It then flew close to the path right across from the residence, and better photos were obtained. We then watched it fly into the cypress trees and on the hillside around the residence and path. It would disappear easily, and then reappear in an instant. Awesome looks.   ID'ed as CAKI due to lack of white on outer rectrices, white chin and malar, yellow on breast not extending to upper breast, short tail, and overall grayness of the bird. Fairly worn. WEKI and other yellow-bellied kingbird sps. ruled out by the above field marks. Mark got some great flight shots. Preliminarily aged and sexed as adult female due to slightly emarginated outer primaries, not nearly as much as would be expected for an adult male, and juvs lack this feature on primary tips. The bird vocalized very briefly twice, but nothing diagnostic. Sweet bird!

Observation Details: Kingbirds with white chins that contrasted with their darker gray heads and chests. Their tails had pale tips to them, with no outer tail feathers. Also, the vocalizations were consistent with that of Cassin's.  East Wing: During the entire time east of the bridge, we observed only one adult foraging on the far fence line.  We assume dispersal of that family group.  West Wing: One adult was continually calling from a large sycamore tree south of the bridge, while several juveniles were being fed by the other adult from bare branches.  Eventually, that second adult descended to the base of an elderberry bush, near where the dirt road goes north into the orchard.  Three juveniles joined that adult, and each of them was fed earwigs that the adult extracted from the crevice of that bush.  As time went on, the juveniles dispersed, and the adult fed one or another of them more sporadically, while the first adult kept on vocalizing.

Continuing county level mega found this morning by A. Merritt. 5th county record per eBird, I believe.  Huge shout-out to Alex for the find, LC for the heads up, and Everett and Bob for the solid recon. Teamwork makes the dream work.  We missed it on our first pass and walked to the tree near the lighthouse steps where Everett had it earlier, without luck. When we returned to the area around the bathrooms, we immediately saw it on the hillside slightly to the north. It then flew close to the path right across from the residence, and better photos were obtained. We then watched it fly into the cypress trees and on the hillside around the residence and path. It would disappear easily, and then reappear in an instant. Awesome looks.   ID'ed as CAKI due to lack of white on outer rectrices, white chin and malar, yellow on breast not extending to upper breast, short tail, and overall grayness of the bird. Fairly worn. WEKI and other yellow-bellied kingbird sp. ruled out by the above field marks. Mark got some great flight shots. Preliminarily aged and sexed as adult female due to slightly emarginated outer primaries, not nearly as much as would be expected for an adult male, and juvs lack this feature on primary tips. Open to feedback about age/sex. The bird vocalized very briefly twice, but nothing diagnostic. Sweet bird!

This puzzling (and silent)  kingbird was seen atop the oaks in the mostly open  field between the Gulf Pier Picnic Area and the park road.  It didn't stay long as it was driven off by both a Blue Jay and a Northern Mockingbird. It was last seen northbound, very high, over the main park road.  I spent about 15 minutes searching the wires and snags north of the fort, but was unable to re-locate the bird.  Initially, I would not have noticed it if it hadn't been for a mockingbird chasing it from out of one of the field's small oaks.  The images show that this bird has a dark gray head and nape. The back is dark grayish with olive tones. The darker head and breast with a white chin is indicative of Cassin's. The gray breast blends to an olive/pale yellow belly. The bill size is not out of range for Cassin's.  Some Cassin's have a notched tail and buffy tail tips are a feature of Cassin's - see pix 2, 5 and 6.  I could see no white along the outer edge of the tail feathers, which would suggest Western.  **  Details and images sent to FLA Ornithological Society Records Committee within a week of this sighting.  On 2 Jan 2022 I was informed by FOSRC that the sighting was accepted.

Media notes: Cassin's Kingbird, first seen by Guy McCaskie, here photographed by Curtis A. Marantz on 18 August 2021 along International Road in the southern part of Niland, Imperial County, California.
Observation Details: McCaskie spotted this bird on the utility wires over International Road opposite the yards just north of Pound Road, where it remained despite some movement for the remainder of our visit.  During this period, we watched the kingbird fly out into the field to the east of International Road, in which it perched on some stalks along a band of vegetation, and we also saw it fly into one of the large cottonwoods in a yard on the west side of the road, but this bird spent much of its time perched in the open on the wires, from which it would sally outward to take flying pretty that may have represented dragonflies.  We never heard this bird vocalize. This was a large, heavy-bodied flycatcher with overall proportions that were similar to those of the Western Kingbirds that were in the same area.  I further noted that the bill tapered from a base that was relatively deep for a flycatcher to a blunt tip along a culmen that was straight for most of its length, and also that the bill would have extended backward on the face to a point near the rear edge of the auriculars, so the bill overall was neither exceptionally long nor short.  The forehead was sloping, and the crown was gently rounded, all on a head that was unremarkably in length for a kingbird.  The neck short and inconspicuous, and the body was plump and full-chested, with a posture that was roughly diagonal when the bird perched on the wires.  I saw this bird mostly from the front, so I was only able to get an impression that the primary projection was roughly comparable to the length of the exposed secondaries, yet I could see clearly that the wingtips reached right to the tips of tapered undertail-coverts that themselves reached almost halfway out the tail.  The tail appeared to be a little longer than the length of the body without the head and neck, and it was parallel-sided and square-tipped though maybe with a very subtle notch in the center.  I did not think the legs and feet were at all remarkable for a kingbird. What really characterized this bird was the dark, almost slate-gray color to the head, neck, breast and sides.  Contrasting with the dark gray of the face an breast was a well-defined white throat that extended from the chin down maybe halfway across the throat and out into the malar region, where the rear edges were curved.  I further noted that the dark gray on the lower throat and breast extended down at least to the junction of the breast and belly, and also onto the adjacent portions of the sides and maybe even the foreflanks.  The demarcation between the gray of the breast and sides, and the yellow that characterized the belly, flanks, and undertail coverts, was relatively sharp and extending more or less straight across the body, though maybe with a weak projection upward in the center.  My impression was that the yellow on the belly, flanks, and undertail coverts was paler than on a Tropical Kingbird, but it was not unusual for a Cassin’s.  The underside of the tail appeared to be almost entirely black, and even though I noted slightly paler edges to the outer feathers, these edges were not white, not overly conspicuous, and we never from below no suggestion of a pale tip to the tail. I never clearly saw this bird’s back, the wingtips, or the upperside of the tail, but I was able to see the closed wings sufficiently well to note that the wing coverts were quite dusky, but with pale fringes that were narrow and relatively inconspicuous, but also relatively well-defined. I am confident that the bill was black, but my recollection now is only that I noted the eyes as being dark in the field, and I cannot now remember even this much about the legs or feet, but I suspect all will be evident from my photos.

Locality: Chestnut Hill Lane - Cassin's Kingbird location
Observation Details: First seen as I was driving down the road, just north of the intersection. It flew right in front of me, and I knew it was different right away. When it banked and flew off to the side of the road I saw the yellowish belly and dark tail and initially thought this was a Western Kingbird. I pulled over and got out of my car. In a short time I was looking at the bird a little ways (100 feet) off the road. I throught I needed photos so I got my camera out and started shooting. I put out the alert to my local Telegram group and put a few of the photos on here and after a short discussiion with several others, we realized this was a Cassin's Kingbird instead. Within 45 minutes I had six other local birders here and we all had great scope views. The bird was very skittish and would not allow people to get close to it, and when a car would come down the road it flushed away from the roadside and landed out in the field aways. After a short time it would return to the roadside area and hunt over the grasses in the ditch. It would then land in the plowed field, anywhere from a foot to ten feet away from the edge of the grass. When I first saw it, and before other arrived, it did land a few times in the middle of the gravel road.   This bird had a medium colored yellow belly, a dark gray hooded head and a clearly seen whitish chin area. The tail was dark, but not a solid black like I've seen on Western Kingbirds. I'll post photos and at least two videos I took of it.

Locality: US-CA-San Jose-899 E Saint James St - 37.3478x-121.8750
Observation Details: Kingbird w/ pale-tipped tail. Head, breast, and upper back gray, all about the same color except slightly darker behind eye and between eye and bill.  Gradually fading to a lighter gray back with just a tinge of green. Wings brown. Clean white chin extending back under eye contrasting noticeably with surrounding gray. Gray breast gradually changing to yellow belly and under tail covs. Tail dark brown with pale but not white tip. Bill about the same length as from base of bill to eye. “Flycatching” camphor fruits from street trees and regurgitating seeds in the street. Perching on wires.  Distinguished from tropical and couch’s by gray, not green back and breast, smaller bill, and tail pattern; from western by tail pattern and darker gray breast.

Had to get an oil change this morning but was able to join the crew and sweep their flycatchers and Kingbirds leftovers.

Media notes: Cassin's Kingbird, first seen by Guy McCaskie, here photographed by Curtis A. Marantz on 18 August 2021 along International Road in the southern part of Niland, Imperial County, California.
Observation Details: McCaskie spotted this bird on the utility wires over International Road opposite the yards just north of Pound Road, where it remained despite some movement for the remainder of our visit.  During this period, we watched the kingbird fly out into the field to the east of International Road, in which it perched on some stalks along a band of vegetation, and we also saw it fly into one of the large cottonwoods in a yard on the west side of the road, but this bird spent much of its time perched in the open on the wires, from which it would sally outward to take flying pretty that may have represented dragonflies.  We never heard this bird vocalize. This was a large, heavy-bodied flycatcher with overall proportions that were similar to those of the Western Kingbirds that were in the same area.  I further noted that the bill tapered from a base that was relatively deep for a flycatcher to a blunt tip along a culmen that was straight for most of its length, and also that the bill would have extended backward on the face to a point near the rear edge of the auriculars, so the bill overall was neither exceptionally long nor short.  The forehead was sloping, and the crown was gently rounded, all on a head that was unremarkably in length for a kingbird.  The neck short and inconspicuous, and the body was plump and full-chested, with a posture that was roughly diagonal when the bird perched on the wires.  I saw this bird mostly from the front, so I was only able to get an impression that the primary projection was roughly comparable to the length of the exposed secondaries, yet I could see clearly that the wingtips reached right to the tips of tapered undertail-coverts that themselves reached almost halfway out the tail.  The tail appeared to be a little longer than the length of the body without the head and neck, and it was parallel-sided and square-tipped though maybe with a very subtle notch in the center.  I did not think the legs and feet were at all remarkable for a kingbird. What really characterized this bird was the dark, almost slate-gray color to the head, neck, breast and sides.  Contrasting with the dark gray of the face an breast was a well-defined white throat that extended from the chin down maybe halfway across the throat and out into the malar region, where the rear edges were curved.  I further noted that the dark gray on the lower throat and breast extended down at least to the junction of the breast and belly, and also onto the adjacent portions of the sides and maybe even the foreflanks.  The demarcation between the gray of the breast and sides, and the yellow that characterized the belly, flanks, and undertail coverts, was relatively sharp and extending more or less straight across the body, though maybe with a weak projection upward in the center.  My impression was that the yellow on the belly, flanks, and undertail coverts was paler than on a Tropical Kingbird, but it was not unusual for a Cassin’s.  The underside of the tail appeared to be almost entirely black, and even though I noted slightly paler edges to the outer feathers, these edges were not white, not overly conspicuous, and we never from below no suggestion of a pale tip to the tail. I never clearly saw this bird’s back, the wingtips, or the upperside of the tail, but I was able to see the closed wings sufficiently well to note that the wing coverts were quite dusky, but with pale fringes that were narrow and relatively inconspicuous, but also relatively well-defined. I am confident that the bill was black, but my recollection now is only that I noted the eyes as being dark in the field, and I cannot now remember even this much about the legs or feet, but I suspect all will be evident from my photos.

Observation Details: At least 2 or 3 over the whole Haster Basin area.  Two were on the south side and later a single bird was at the northeastern corner of basin. This latter bird, oddly enough, was repeatedly (about every 15 to 20 seconds for several minutes) diving at and trying to drive off the small flock of Brewers Blackbirds that frequently likes to perch atop a power pole at the northeastern corner of the basin. The CAKI would drive off 2 or 3 BRBLs off the cross arm of the pole, but the blackbirds would just circle around and return to their perches on the the pole. So then maybe 15 seconds later, the CAKI would dive at them again. The CAKI kept this up for maybe 5 or 6 minutes that I watched them, but it didn't seem be to having much success in his endeavor. Just seemed odd why it was going to all this trouble in trying to drive off the blackbirds--didn't make any sense. It isn't the nesting season and I didn't see any choice foraging resource at this specific location (like maybe a fruiting shrub or tree that the kingbird might like). Very curious.  I guess just doing a good job living up to its generic name (Tyrannus=tyrant [despot, absolute ruler, etc.).

Once rare, this species seems to be increasing in numbers during our winter months.  Before it was rare to have one.  Today, on a good day, a birder may find a pair or two on the park grounds during the winter months.

Observation Details: Noticed this yellow-bellied tyrannus on a power wire while my husband was fueling up the car, so I grabbed a few photos. I'm not 100% sure -- I'll gladly correct if wrong. The habitat location (inner city, power line, at a gas station of busy streets) is much more typical for Western Kingbird (where these birds are common before they depart) and seems completely off for a Cassin's Kingbird. I'm not seeing white-edged tail feathers, but it's November and a WEKI would be (and this bird appears to be) very worn. The bill doesn't seem large enough for TRKI or COKI so I ruled those out. The throat patch is sort of like a CAKI malar patch, but not as crisp as typical, with a paler throat down the breast also. And the yellow extends quite a bit up the breast for a CAKI, rather than a crisper darker contrast. But I'm seeing so much variation in the online photos of these two species. At this season CAKI is much more likely than WEKI. Unfortunately the bird did not vocalize.

Observation Details: Rarity reported yesterday by May Glynn Williamson, who was kind enough to lead a group of birders there today, and it was present in the same location. Kingbird with gray upper parts, chest and breast, bright lemon-yellow belly, white chin, hooked bill, dark tail with no white outer tail feathers like Western Kingbirds. It was peculiar to see this flycatcher in such cold weather not catching bugs in the air but hunting them in the fields from low perches on plants and in trees flying branch-to-branch much like Yellow-rumped Warblers do when they are fluttering up and around the tree branches.  It also appeared to be eating berries or perhaps spiders, insects or bugs that were on the leaves and berries.  It was "chewing up" and "spitting out" pieces of berries. Very strange, right? None-the-less it seemed to be getting a lot to eat which is good because maybe it will stick around awhile for more people to see. The second shot shows the berry (with twig attached) that it carried to the wire and then decided to discard.

This puzzling (and silent)  kingbird was seen atop the oaks in the mostly open  field between the Gulf Pier Picnic Area and the park road.  It didn't stay long as it was driven off by both a Blue Jay and a Northern Mockingbird. It was last seen northbound, very high, over the main park road.  I spent about 15 minutes searching the wires and snags north of the fort, but was unable to re-locate the bird.  Initially, I would not have noticed it if it hadn't been for a mockingbird chasing it from out of one of the field's small oaks.  The images show that this bird has a dark gray head and nape. The back is dark grayish with olive tones. The darker head and breast with a white chin is indicative of Cassin's. The gray breast blends to an olive/pale yellow belly. The bill size is not out of range for Cassin's.  Some Cassin's have a notched tail and buffy tail tips are a feature of Cassin's - see pix 2, 5 and 6.  I could see no white along the outer edge of the tail feathers, which would suggest Western.  **  Details and images sent to FLA Ornithological Society Records Committee within a week of this sighting.  On 2 Jan 2022 I was informed by FOSRC that the sighting was accepted.

Media notes: Cassin's Kingbird, first seen by Guy McCaskie, here photographed by Curtis A. Marantz on 18 August 2021 along International Road in the southern part of Niland, Imperial County, California.
Observation Details: McCaskie spotted this bird on the utility wires over International Road opposite the yards just north of Pound Road, where it remained despite some movement for the remainder of our visit.  During this period, we watched the kingbird fly out into the field to the east of International Road, in which it perched on some stalks along a band of vegetation, and we also saw it fly into one of the large cottonwoods in a yard on the west side of the road, but this bird spent much of its time perched in the open on the wires, from which it would sally outward to take flying pretty that may have represented dragonflies.  We never heard this bird vocalize. This was a large, heavy-bodied flycatcher with overall proportions that were similar to those of the Western Kingbirds that were in the same area.  I further noted that the bill tapered from a base that was relatively deep for a flycatcher to a blunt tip along a culmen that was straight for most of its length, and also that the bill would have extended backward on the face to a point near the rear edge of the auriculars, so the bill overall was neither exceptionally long nor short.  The forehead was sloping, and the crown was gently rounded, all on a head that was unremarkably in length for a kingbird.  The neck short and inconspicuous, and the body was plump and full-chested, with a posture that was roughly diagonal when the bird perched on the wires.  I saw this bird mostly from the front, so I was only able to get an impression that the primary projection was roughly comparable to the length of the exposed secondaries, yet I could see clearly that the wingtips reached right to the tips of tapered undertail-coverts that themselves reached almost halfway out the tail.  The tail appeared to be a little longer than the length of the body without the head and neck, and it was parallel-sided and square-tipped though maybe with a very subtle notch in the center.  I did not think the legs and feet were at all remarkable for a kingbird. What really characterized this bird was the dark, almost slate-gray color to the head, neck, breast and sides.  Contrasting with the dark gray of the face an breast was a well-defined white throat that extended from the chin down maybe halfway across the throat and out into the malar region, where the rear edges were curved.  I further noted that the dark gray on the lower throat and breast extended down at least to the junction of the breast and belly, and also onto the adjacent portions of the sides and maybe even the foreflanks.  The demarcation between the gray of the breast and sides, and the yellow that characterized the belly, flanks, and undertail coverts, was relatively sharp and extending more or less straight across the body, though maybe with a weak projection upward in the center.  My impression was that the yellow on the belly, flanks, and undertail coverts was paler than on a Tropical Kingbird, but it was not unusual for a Cassin’s.  The underside of the tail appeared to be almost entirely black, and even though I noted slightly paler edges to the outer feathers, these edges were not white, not overly conspicuous, and we never from below no suggestion of a pale tip to the tail. I never clearly saw this bird’s back, the wingtips, or the upperside of the tail, but I was able to see the closed wings sufficiently well to note that the wing coverts were quite dusky, but with pale fringes that were narrow and relatively inconspicuous, but also relatively well-defined. I am confident that the bill was black, but my recollection now is only that I noted the eyes as being dark in the field, and I cannot now remember even this much about the legs or feet, but I suspect all will be evident from my photos.

Kingbirds with dark gray head, gray breast contrasted with white chin. Vocalizations were diagnostic for Cassin's, too.  At one point, one Cassin's and two Western Kingbirds were perched on a fence wire side by side, making for good comparison of size and shape.  I have been observing the same two pairs since March 11.  East Wing pair: When I arrived, the male was chasing off a Swainson's Hawk from the nest tree.  The female briefly left the nest and returned. Over time, tghe bird would leave the nest for a few minutes. Once, the bird left the nest and fluttered its wings in display, but no mating was observed.  The male perched near the nest and chased off Brewer's Blackbirds when they got too close to the nest.  West Wing pair: The nest was unoccupied at first, but then the pair came in and the female got settled into the nest.  The male came down to the fence line and back up to the tree, while the female stayed for the most part on the nest, leaving only once while I was there.

Media notes: Tyrannus flycatcher distinguished from Tropical and Couch's by smaller bill, grayish breast, and very dark tail feathers. Distinguished from Western Kingbird by darker gray head and nape, white cheek that contrasted noticeably with dark gray head, and pale tipped tail feathers. Locality: UCSB North Campus Open Space (formerly Ocean Meadows Golf Course)

Observation Details: Two adults feeding four fledglings in a large magnolia (or similar) tree. Observed over the course of 20 minutes, the juveniles were sometimes huddled together in pairs, or resting individually, sometimes with eyes closed. But mostly they were alert and would gather immediately with short flights when an adult arrived with food. Food deliveries took place every few minutes and included red berries and insects (photos suggest bees). Each food delivery was given to one individual. Adults did not stay with the young for more than a few seconds, although sometimes they perched at the top of the tree for a few minutes at a time. The young called constantly with typical "ch-beer" calls which were slightly thinner and buzzier than the adult calls.

Cassin Kingbird
Observation Details: Found yesterday by Mark Stacy in the SW corner of the Lemoore Sports Complex.   John first saw it yesterday evening (12/12) about 4:30PM as soccer folks were leaving and again this morning about 8:45AM til about 9:30AM with me. Both times it was in the group of trees that appear to be in an “L” shape which can be viewed as you stand along the fence on the southern side of the complex by the railroad tracks and you look North.   These trees, some with small red berries, are closest to the area where the field slopes down. The line of tree goes north a short distance then turns east by a couple of blue trash cans and high ladder-like light standards.  The Cassin’s Kingbird remained mostly in the leafless trees with red berries (pistache?) and flew down to the ground several times. When last seen it flew west towards the parking lot, and probably south over the railroad tracks toward some more red berried trees.  Photo isn’t the best quality since I was shooting thru the wired fence.

Observation Details: Dark gray breast, distinctive white throat, yellow belly, black tail with pale tip instead of white edge feathers, chi-beer call. After recognizing our first Cassin's, we began to realize they were almost all Cassin's in this area dominated by open Ponderosa Pine forest, south of the Bull Mtns.  Might have expected this if we had read "Birds of Montana"...
Including at least 5 in the "Pine Barrens," which seems to be optimal habitat for the species.

Locality: Pumpkin Center Road, Jefferson Davis Section, Hayes, Louisiana, US
Observation Details: Silent. 30.0748502, -92.9331005. Found about 200 ft away while scoping the tree line, looking SW from Pumpkin Center Rd., to scan through a blackbird flock. This bird was at the east end of that flock and slowly worked its way east toward the road. Initial scoped views piqued my interest for being a possible Cassin's - the head and chest looked dark gray with the white chin and "mustache" contrastingly strongly. Where the tree line met Pumpkin Center Rd., there was a raised solid access road to the west with an open gate. I waited at the gate as the bird continued to work its way east, slowly, as the blackbird flock did the same. After another 20 minutes, the bird got within good range to get profile photos, and up-close scoped views. The initial head pattern impression remained, and although there was a thin white edge (wear?) to the outer tail feather, the outer webbing of R6 was black, which should rule out Western Kingbird.

Adult and 3 fledglings. I watched the family for about 1/2 hour, and never saw a second adult. Adult was consistently bringing food to all young. Fledglings were also making flights (5 - 75m in length) and doing a little bit of foraging on their own. After their flights, they soon returned to one spot, and waited for food. They still seemed pretty dependent on the adult. Adult giving chi-beer call often. Fledglings giving near constant chatter that sounded like a modification of the chi-beer call. A couple hours later, I saw all 3 fledglings lined up close together on a telephone wire about 350m from the original location. White throat contrasting with gray chest.

Locality: Chestnut Hill Lane - Cassin's Kingbird location
Observation Details: First seen as I was driving down the road, just north of the intersection. It flew right in front of me, and I knew it was different right away. When it banked and flew off to the side of the road I saw the yellowish belly and dark tail and initially thought this was a Western Kingbird. I pulled over and got out of my car. In a short time I was looking at the bird a little ways (100 feet) off the road. I throught I needed photos so I got my camera out and started shooting. I put out the alert to my local Telegram group and put a few of the photos on here and after a short discussiion with several others, we realized this was a Cassin's Kingbird instead. Within 45 minutes I had six other local birders here and we all had great scope views. The bird was very skittish and would not allow people to get close to it, and when a car would come down the road it flushed away from the roadside and landed out in the field aways. After a short time it would return to the roadside area and hunt over the grasses in the ditch. It would then land in the plowed field, anywhere from a foot to ten feet away from the edge of the grass. When I first saw it, and before other arrived, it did land a few times in the middle of the gravel road.   This bird had a medium colored yellow belly, a dark gray hooded head and a clearly seen whitish chin area. The tail was dark, but not a solid black like I've seen on Western Kingbirds. I'll post photos and at least two videos I took of it.

Media notes: This is a recently fledged Cassin's Kingbird, photographed in a tree along the fence over the river.  I have chosen this photo as it clearly shows the abrupt delineation of the white "mustache" pattern, under the center of the eye.
Observation Details: In the trees along the fence, near the bathrooms.  We have been lucky in the park, as it appears that both Cassin's Kingbirds and Western Kingbirds have fledged young this summer, which offers an opportunity for comparison.  They can be difficult to distinguish, particularly at this early stage.  The color differences in the throat and chest are not yet clearly established.  In order to differentiate between them, I have been carefully photographing first the underside of the tails, before getting additional photos; noting the presence, or absence, of clearly defined white outer tail feathers.  As a result, I have found some subtle differences, particularly in the "mustache" area.  I am not sure if these have any diagnostic relevance, but in my photos I have noticed the white "mustache" in the Cassin's juveniles ends sharply beneath the middle of the eye.  In the clearly marked Western Kingbird juveniles, the white area under the eye continues back into the malar area, diminishing gradually toward the back.  This has proven useful to me in instances when the "dark gray throat and chest" are not yet clearly defined.  I have included comparison photos of two birds of similar age.

Observation Details: Kingbirds with white chins that contrasted with gray breasts, tails with pale terminal bands, and vocalizations consistent with Cassin's. East Wing (east of the bridge) - This site continues to be inconclusive.  We heard one adult briefly calling farther south and more distant from the presumed nest tree. West Wing - At about 8:30 a.m., we saw one adult perched low next to a juvenile and two more juveniles perched higher in the nest tree.  Eventually, the third juvenile joined the other two while the adult went into the tree.  At one point, we heard two adults calling.  At 8:40 a.m., one adult called noisily and flew out of the tree across the field, followed by the three juveniles.  All four birds perched on the fence line and the utility wire above the fence. There were some vocalization, and then a juvenile came closer to the adult, briefly fluttered its wings and was fed.  At 8:55 a.m., all four birds flew together swiftly into the sycamore grove northeast of the fence and the nest tree.  We may have been lucky enough to witness the beginning of dispersal.

Observation Details: Kingbirds with white chins that contrasted with gray breasts, tails with pale terminal bands, and vocalizations consistent with Cassin's.  East Wing - This location continues to provide us with sparse information.  We heard the "call outbursts" associated with a pair of adults, but never saw any adults or fledglings from the distant probable nest site well to the south of the road. West Wing - We immediately saw an adult at the crown of the nest tree.  Eventually, we found two fledglings close to each other, waiting to be fed. Then a third fledgling joined the other two. That surprised us, since we had only seen two chicks being fed in the nest on July 1 and June 24. There was a long interval of waiting, during which time the largest fledgling picked at leaves around it. Then we observed a rapid succession of seven feedings of all three fledglings by both adults.

Observation Details: ***mega; first state record; found by Andy Baldelli earlier in the day; ph. Original notes: This stunning Cassin’s Kingbird showed brilliant white malar and chin, the latter subtly suffused with gray toward the lower throat. A faint dark line between malar and throat may either have been a shadow resulting from the division between the feather tracts or an actual plumage feature.  The breast and head were deeply gray, contrasting strongly with the white throat and yellow belly. Because of the intensity of the gray on the face, the subtly darker mask didn’t stand out very much. The black bill was short (similar to WEKI, shorter than TRKI) but deep and featured a distinctly curved culmen.  In these last two respects, the bill differed from my conception of that of a typical WEKI. The back was dull greenish, the wings brownish with conspicuous pale edges to the coverts and tertials (one of the latter of which had been replaced on the left wing), and the tail black and square-tipped. Especially during feeding sallies, it was obvious that the tail was categorically blacker than the rest of the upperparts. The outer rectrices showed very little if any lateral pale edging to the distal portions of the outer webs. The rectrices were visibly worn and showed narrow, indistinct pale tips that appeared off-white to buffy, depending on angle and lighting. The primary projection was markedly shorter than in WEKI, and the projecting primary tips did not appear to be obviously notched. In flight overhead, it was obvious to me that wingtips were much rounder (less pointed) than in WEKI, and a photo of the bird with open wings demonstrates both this character and the lack of obvious notches to the outer primaries (indicating a hatching-year individual). The small bill and black, square-tipped tail readily exclude TRKI/COKI. The deeply gray head and breast, contrastingly brilliant white malar and throat, and rounded wingtips readily exclude WEKI.

continuing

*Late* Immediately started calling as soon as I stepped out the door of my house. Rapid, excited "chippur!" similar to, but much more rapid than the call note of a Scarlet Tanager. Watched for 15-20 minutes as it actively hawked insects from the trees and powerlines in the alleyway. Juvenile bird, with crisp buffy edging to coverts. Bright, buffy terminal tail tip. Bright yellow belly, darker gray head and chest with whitish moustachial mark. Separated from WEKI by darker gray head, white moustache, overall shorter bill, buffy tail tip with no obvious white outer tail feathers, and call. Photos.

This puzzling (and silent)  kingbird was seen atop the oaks in the mostly open  field between the Gulf Pier Picnic Area and the park road.  It didn't stay long as it was driven off by both a Blue Jay and a Northern Mockingbird. It was last seen northbound, very high, over the main park road.  I spent about 15 minutes searching the wires and snags north of the fort, but was unable to re-locate the bird.  Initially, I would not have noticed it if it hadn't been for a mockingbird chasing it from out of one of the field's small oaks.  The images show that this bird has a dark gray head and nape. The back is dark grayish with olive tones. The darker head and breast with a white chin is indicative of Cassin's. The gray breast blends to an olive/pale yellow belly. The bill size is not out of range for Cassin's.  Some Cassin's have a notched tail and buffy tail tips are a feature of Cassin's - see pix 2, 5 and 6.  I could see no white along the outer edge of the tail feathers, which would suggest Western.  **  Details and images sent to FLA Ornithological Society Records Committee within a week of this sighting.  On 2 Jan 2022 I was informed by FOSRC that the sighting was accepted.

Continuing and awesome:

The two birds we saw had white malars contrasting with gray chins, tails with white tips, darker  gray head and breast. The two birds we heard had the diagnostic calls of Cassin's Kingbirds.  Locations: One bird was still on the wire at Bell Road.  The other visible kingbird was on the fence just east of the first sycamore tree on the south, from which we heard another bird calling.  The fourth kingbird was heard from a distant grove on the southwest side of the aqueduct.

Xavier and I looked at each of these birds carefully.  Each of them had a darker grey head and breast than a Western Kingbird. Their bills were thicker, and the white malars were strongly contrasted with their dark chins.  None had white outer edges on the tail, but instead a pale band at the base of the tail. Furthermore, when any of the pairs of birds vocalized, their calls were consistent with Cassin's Kingbirds, not Western Kingbirds. i am quite familiar with the calls of both species of kingbirdss.  In fact, we saw no Westen Kingbirds at all that day.  Xavier has some photos,which he can put on his post.   There were three pairs and an unpaired adult.  All three pairs seemed to be on territory: one pair on Bell Road one mile before the bridge, the other pair and single bird on a fence going into private property, and the third pair in the first tree to the southeast of the bridge as you face west..  No evidence of nesting was seen yet.

Observation Details: Originally entered as yellow-bellied kingbird. First impression was Western Kingbird based on pale gray throat (vs. Cassin's white/gray contrasting throat); however, the morning sun was shining brightly on this perched individual. Barely visible white outer tail feathers seen in photos, but Cassin's can have feather wear, so we are cautious about this field mark. Unable to see back to assess contrast with wings. Kimball kindly provided helpful observations pointing to Cassin's. Chin and partial malar look contrastingly white (though hard to tell exact pattern); crown looks very dark gray; and thin whitish edge to outer rectrix looks fine for a fresh-plumaged Cassin's [Western would have a black tail with bolder white edge.]

Rarity reported yesterday by May Glynn Williamson, who was kind enough to lead a group of birders there today, and it was present in the same location. Kingbird with gray upper parts, chest and breast, bright lemon-yellow belly, white chin, hooked bill, dark tail with no white outer tail feathers like Western Kingbirds. It was peculiar to see this flycatcher in such cold weather not catching bugs in the air but hunting them in the fields from low perches on plants and in trees flying branch-to-branch much like Yellow-rumped Warblers do when they are fluttering up and around the tree branches.  It also appeared to be eating berries or perhaps spiders, insects or bugs that were on the leaves and berries.  It was "chewing up" and "spitting out" pieces of berries. Very strange, right? None-the-less it seemed to be getting a lot to eat which is good because maybe it will stick around awhile for more people to see. The second shot shows the berry (with twig attached) that it carried to the wire and then decided to discard.

Second county record found this afternoon by Cameron Tescher. Observed for about an hour and a half, working its way south. It was initially hanging out in the willows lining the CR 103 pond, it then flew across the pond and gave some awesome looks on the telephone wires in front of the residences. Dark gray kingbird that had a bright white chin; bright lemon belly that contrasted with a dark gray breast; dark tail that had a white terminal band on the tips of the rectrices. Vocalized a number of times, a “veeeer” call. Photos and recordings to be posted

Media notes: This Cassin's Kingbird carried this berry {with twig attached} to the wire probably to eat it but decided to discard it.  I have shots of the bird watching it fall all the way to the ground. Normally I would not post such a poor quality shot, but found the behavior strange enough to share it with the group.
Observation Details: Rarity reported yesterday by May Glynn Williamson, who was kind enough to lead a group of birders there today, and it was present in the same location. Kingbird with gray upper parts, chest and breast, bright lemon-yellow belly, white chin, hooked bill, dark tail with no white outer tail feathers like Western Kingbirds. It was peculiar to see this flycatcher in such cold weather not catching bugs in the air but hunting them in the fields from low perches on plants and in trees flying branch-to-branch much like Yellow-rumped Warblers do when they are fluttering up and around the tree branches.  It also appeared to be eating berries or perhaps spiders, insects or bugs that were on the leaves and berries.  It was "chewing up" and "spitting out" pieces of berries. Very strange, right? None-the-less it seemed to be getting a lot to eat which is good because maybe it will stick around awhile for more people to see. The second shot shows the berry (with twig attached) that it carried to the wire and then decided to discard.

Locality: Pumpkin Center Road, Jefferson Davis Section, Hayes, Louisiana, US
Observation Details: Silent. 30.0748502, -92.9331005. Found about 200 ft away while scoping the tree line, looking SW from Pumpkin Center Rd., to scan through a blackbird flock. This bird was at the east end of that flock and slowly worked its way east toward the road. Initial scoped views piqued my interest for being a possible Cassin's - the head and chest looked dark gray with the white chin and "mustache" contrastingly strongly. Where the tree line met Pumpkin Center Rd., there was a raised solid access road to the west with an open gate. I waited at the gate as the bird continued to work its way east, slowly, as the blackbird flock did the same. After another 20 minutes, the bird got within good range to get profile photos, and up-close scoped views. The initial head pattern impression remained, and although there was a thin white edge (wear?) to the outer tail feather, the outer webbing of R6 was black, which should rule out Western Kingbird.

First reported early  yesterday afternoon by Nicole Shangi. The bird was observed and photographed by local birders. The bird was identified yesterday evening as a Cassin's Kingbird. Thanks to Cameron Chevalier for getting the word out once the CAKI ID was made. Tyrannus kingbird with grey head and upper breast, white throat patch extending to under the eye, and a yellow belly. Dark tail with no white edges in the outer rectrices. The bird was observed regularly pumping its tail as it actively fed on insects in the trees at 625 Point Pelee Drive (formerly Birdies Perch). Record photos taken.

Observation Details: Bright yellow belly, notched tail. I initially thought it might be a Western Kingbird, but it had no white on the outer tail feathers, even when it flew up and landed back on the wire. The yellow does not go as far up as one might expect. The head is a light gray, not dark, the chest is not dark like a Cassin's. The next week in the same area (right around parking lot at entrance to Border Field Park which is also entrance for Goat Canyon) a tropical kingbird was seen, better photograph of well-notched tail. Thought this might be same one. That one is on a Border Field Park checklist https://ebird.org/checklist/S118978785

Observation Details: Tally, lots of big groups.

Adult and 3 fledglings. I watched the family for about 1/2 hour, and never saw a second adult. Adult was consistently bringing food to all young. Fledglings were also making flights (5 - 75m in length) and doing a little bit of foraging on their own. After their flights, they soon returned to one spot, and waited for food. They still seemed pretty dependent on the adult. Adult giving chi-beer call often. Fledglings giving near constant chatter that sounded like a modification of the chi-beer call. A couple hours later, I saw all 3 fledglings lined up close together on a telephone wire about 350m from the original location. White throat contrasting with gray chest.

Unfortunately the bird only stayed for about a minute. I looked away for a few seconds and didn't even see which direction it flew. I did not see it again from the time I saw it until I left around 1100. Originally marked it as a Cassin's/Western Kingbird but have adjusted it after being reviewed.

Kingbirds with white chins that contrasted with gray breasts, tails with pale terminal bands, and vocalizations consistent with Cassin's.  East Wing - This location continues to provide us with sparse information.  We heard the "call outbursts" associated with a pair of adults, but never saw any adults or fledglings from the distant probable nest site well to the south of the road. West Wing - We immediately saw an adult at the crown of the nest tree.  Eventually, we found two fledglings close to each other, waiting to be fed. Then a third fledgling joined the other two. That surprised us, since we had only seen two chicks being fed in the nest on July 1 and June 24. There was a long interval of waiting, during which time the largest fledgling picked at leaves around it. Then we observed a rapid succession of seven feedings of all three fledglings by both adults.

Locality: Ballona Creek: Overland to Ballona Creek Bridge (Marina Del Rey)
Observation Details: At 19:20, returned to site where I had observed Tropical Kingbird earlier (Approx. where Ballona Creek meets Slauson). The Tropical Kingbird was still there (note photos under Tropical Kingbird taken in evening light). There was another Kingbird (presumed Cassin's though not confirmed [relatively long beak; contrasting color and appearing darker gray though lighting conditions not ideal]) perched around 10 meters away on an adjacent overhead wire. It was turned away with tail facing me, so it made it hard to positively ID. The Tropical Kingbird flew out of view after a minute or so. At 19:22 another bird landed on the part of the wire where the Tropical Kingbird was. This bird was a Cassin's Kingbird, confirmed with photos and audio recordings of vocalizations.   Another Cassin's Kingbird heard and recorded in tree near Sepulveda at 19:40. Hooded Oriole in nearby tree also heard and can be heard in recording.

Media notes: Adult feeding fledgling
Observation Details: Two adults feeding four fledglings in a large magnolia (or similar) tree. Observed over the course of 20 minutes, the juveniles were sometimes huddled together in pairs, or resting individually, sometimes with eyes closed. But mostly they were alert and would gather immediately with short flights when an adult arrived with food. Food deliveries took place every few minutes and included red berries and insects (photos suggest bees). Each food delivery was given to one individual. Adults did not stay with the young for more than a few seconds, although sometimes they perched at the top of the tree for a few minutes at a time. The young called constantly with typical "ch-beer" calls which were slightly thinner and buzzier than the adult calls.

Found with migrating Scissor-tailed Flycatchers as it perched on utility wires near a pond on Ramfield Road, about 1/2 mile west of Flour Bluff Drive. As I was driving by, I noticed a dark, chunky yellow-bellied Tyrannus which I immediately thought of as Cassin's.  I pulled over, got some  mediocre shots, called in some other birders, who also saw the bird. My dictated notes: " I have a Cassin's Kingbird on Ramfield Rd about 1/2 mile west of Flour Bluff Drive....sitting on a utility wire, on top wire next to a pond on the north side of road...associating with some STFLs...I first glanced the bird as I was driving past, and it look to broad-chested and too dark for any other yellow-bellied tyrannus kingbird...and this bird has a very dark gray crown.. and it has a bright white "bowtie" chin, in complete contrast to the chest, which is very dark gray...the bird appears to have a pale, what appears to be buff terminal band to the tail (visible in 71219671 shot) ... the tail looks fairly short, maybe shorter than other tyrannus, but this could have to do with the chunky structure of the bird.... the breast is quite dark gray, extending down to the central belly. It appears the wing coverts are more scalloped and lighter than the back. There seems to be a white edge to one of the INNER retrices ( I later determined this was simply a white shaft (rachis) to R3 or R4.) although it is not an outer feather, one of the inner retrices"       " It sallied up 3-4 times, no vocalizations as of yet. I have looked at the bird about 20 minutes now...:  This would represent the first documented record of this species for Nueces County, although there have been a couple of compelling sight records.

Observation Details: ***mega; first state record; found by Andy Baldelli earlier in the day; ph. Original notes: This stunning Cassin’s Kingbird showed brilliant white malar and chin, the latter subtly suffused with gray toward the lower throat. A faint dark line between malar and throat may either have been a shadow resulting from the division between the feather tracts or an actual plumage feature.  The breast and head were deeply gray, contrasting strongly with the white throat and yellow belly. Because of the intensity of the gray on the face, the subtly darker mask didn’t stand out very much. The black bill was short (similar to WEKI, shorter than TRKI) but deep and featured a distinctly curved culmen.  In these last two respects, the bill differed from my conception of that of a typical WEKI. The back was dull greenish, the wings brownish with conspicuous pale edges to the coverts and tertials (one of the latter of which had been replaced on the left wing), and the tail black and square-tipped. Especially during feeding sallies, it was obvious that the tail was categorically blacker than the rest of the upperparts. The outer rectrices showed very little if any lateral pale edging to the distal portions of the outer webs. The rectrices were visibly worn and showed narrow, indistinct pale tips that appeared off-white to buffy, depending on angle and lighting. The primary projection was markedly shorter than in WEKI, and the projecting primary tips did not appear to be obviously notched. In flight overhead, it was obvious to me that wingtips were much rounder (less pointed) than in WEKI, and a photo of the bird with open wings demonstrates both this character and the lack of obvious notches to the outer primaries (indicating a hatching-year individual). The small bill and black, square-tipped tail readily exclude TRKI/COKI. The deeply gray head and breast, contrastingly brilliant white malar and throat, and rounded wingtips readily exclude WEKI.

This puzzling (and silent)  kingbird was seen atop the oaks in the mostly open  field between the Gulf Pier Picnic Area and the park road.  It didn't stay long as it was driven off by both a Blue Jay and a Northern Mockingbird. It was last seen northbound, very high, over the main park road.  I spent about 15 minutes searching the wires and snags north of the fort, but was unable to re-locate the bird.  Initially, I would not have noticed it if it hadn't been for a mockingbird chasing it from out of one of the field's small oaks.  The images show that this bird has a dark gray head and nape. The back is dark grayish with olive tones. The darker head and breast with a white chin is indicative of Cassin's. The gray breast blends to an olive/pale yellow belly. The bill size is not out of range for Cassin's.  Some Cassin's have a notched tail and buffy tail tips are a feature of Cassin's - see pix 2, 5 and 6.  I could see no white along the outer edge of the tail feathers, which would suggest Western.  **  Details and images sent to FLA Ornithological Society Records Committee within a week of this sighting.  On 2 Jan 2022 I was informed by FOSRC that the sighting was accepted.
